WEBVTT

00:04.352 --> 00:04.526
.

00:04.569 --> 00:06.441
- You're all so photogenic.

00:06.484 --> 00:08.269
- Cara's clearly making
a move on Gallo.

00:08.312 --> 00:09.705
- She is something.

00:09.748 --> 00:11.794
- I have to move to Oregon.

00:11.837 --> 00:14.231
- I wanna stay together.
- Me too.

00:14.275 --> 00:16.233
- When I lost my family,
it was the fire chief

00:16.277 --> 00:17.669
that made sure I didn't
fall through the cracks.

00:17.713 --> 00:18.757
I think it's great those boys

00:18.801 --> 00:20.194
are gonna have you
in their lives.

00:20.237 --> 00:22.065
[dramatic music]

00:22.109 --> 00:23.458
- I thank that Lord
that Sister Montclair

00:23.501 --> 00:24.546
wasn't hurt in the fire.

00:24.589 --> 00:25.721
- I wasn't there.

00:25.764 --> 00:27.114
- I think we go right
to Father Anthony

00:27.157 --> 00:28.332
and find out what he's hiding.

00:28.376 --> 00:30.769
- Anybody home?

00:30.813 --> 00:32.467
[muffled screams]

00:32.510 --> 00:34.121
- I need an ambulance
at Saint Sebastian's rectory.

00:34.164 --> 00:35.687
Suspect headed north.

00:35.731 --> 00:37.515
- Can we talk to him?
It's urgent.

00:37.559 --> 00:40.170
- We're gonna have to keep him
in a medically-induced coma.

00:42.129 --> 00:45.088
[suspenseful music]

00:45.132 --> 00:46.394
♪

00:46.437 --> 00:47.960
- This is all of it?

00:48.004 --> 00:49.875
- Everything they could pull
off the PODS after the hack.

00:49.919 --> 00:52.443
- I just got off with Atwater.
Forensics is a bust.

00:52.487 --> 00:55.272
No prints, fibers, blood.

00:55.316 --> 00:57.144
Any sign of your guy?

00:57.187 --> 00:59.189
- We can only track him about
three blocks from the rectory.

00:59.233 --> 01:01.235
Then we lose him completely.

01:01.278 --> 01:02.584
- So our only
hope of identifying him

01:02.627 --> 01:04.281
is Father Anthony
coming out of a coma.

01:04.325 --> 01:07.110
- And that could take weeks.
If at all.

01:07.154 --> 01:08.633
- PD's all in on this case now,

01:08.677 --> 01:11.767
so I can't really justify
keeping you from 51 anymore.

01:11.810 --> 01:13.334
If you want to go back--

01:13.377 --> 01:15.118
- So OFI is dropping
the case then?

01:15.162 --> 01:16.337
- Of course not.

01:16.380 --> 01:17.686
We have
a dangerous arsonist out there.

01:17.729 --> 01:19.296
- Then I'm not going anywhere.

01:19.340 --> 01:20.906
Boden's okay with me
staying on.

01:20.950 --> 01:22.734
- That's good to hear.

01:22.778 --> 01:25.389
So what's the next move?

01:25.433 --> 01:27.478
- I say we go back
to Sister Montclair.

01:27.522 --> 01:29.219
Father Anthony
thought she knew something,

01:29.263 --> 01:30.525
even if she doesn't realize it.

01:30.568 --> 01:32.135
- Maybe we just didn't ask
the right questions.

01:32.179 --> 01:33.832
- Okay. Go talk to her.

01:33.876 --> 01:40.883
♪

01:45.540 --> 01:47.498
- Anyone seen our relief
lieutenant yet?

01:47.542 --> 01:48.760
- Nope.

01:48.804 --> 01:50.762
- Is that him?

01:50.806 --> 01:52.764
- Uh, no, Capp. That is not.

01:52.808 --> 01:55.593
- You need glasses.
- Did you swipe my queen?

01:55.637 --> 01:56.638
- Morning.
- Good morning.

01:56.681 --> 01:57.856
- Do you know anything

01:57.900 --> 01:59.728
about the floater
lieutenant for this shift?

01:59.771 --> 02:02.209
- Just that his name's Pelham.
He's not here yet?

02:02.252 --> 02:03.732
- Pelham?

02:03.775 --> 02:04.820
Yeah, he's right over there.

02:04.863 --> 02:07.170
- Ah. Mm.

02:07.214 --> 02:09.346
- Yeah, we noticed
a hydraulic leak last night.

02:09.390 --> 02:10.913
Pelham came in early
and said he could fix it,

02:10.956 --> 02:13.655
so he grabbed a wrench
and got on in there.

02:20.270 --> 02:22.359
- [groans]
- Lieutenant Pelham?

02:22.403 --> 02:25.188
Randall McHolland.
Chauffeur and aerial operator.

02:25.232 --> 02:28.931
- Ah. Jason Pelham.

02:28.974 --> 02:30.715
- You look familiar.

02:30.759 --> 02:32.674
- Did you work the
Copes Warehouse fire last year?

02:32.717 --> 02:33.805
Back of the Yards?

02:33.849 --> 02:35.242
- No, but that's where
I've seen you.

02:35.285 --> 02:37.983
On TV, hauling those
two kids outta there.

02:38.027 --> 02:39.507
- You know,
it's the craziest thing.

02:39.550 --> 02:41.813
I'm floating at 41,
thinking I'll catch a few winks

02:41.857 --> 02:44.642
since it's usually
the slowest house in Chicago.

02:44.686 --> 02:46.557
I got a three-alarm
hellscape instead.

02:46.601 --> 02:48.820
- What a rescue, though.
- Ah.

02:48.864 --> 02:50.300
Just right place, right time.

02:55.262 --> 02:57.786
- Lemme guess.
Something from Casey?

02:57.829 --> 02:59.396
- It's been hard to connect
over the phone

02:59.440 --> 03:01.703
because of our schedules,
so he sent me a letter.

03:01.746 --> 03:03.313
- Aww.
- I know.

03:03.357 --> 03:04.662
- Look how cute
his handwriting is.

03:04.706 --> 03:05.837
- Real cute.

03:05.881 --> 03:07.448
- You book your flight
to Portland yet?

03:07.491 --> 03:10.668
- Yep--I fly out in ten days
and seven hours.

03:10.712 --> 03:12.714
But who's counting?
- Mm-hmm.

03:12.757 --> 03:14.411
- Oh, hey, Gallo.

03:14.455 --> 03:15.630
Casey said to give this to you.

03:22.985 --> 03:27.381
- Four pounds beef brisket,
one tablespoon brown sugar.

03:27.424 --> 03:29.252
What is this?

03:31.472 --> 03:33.735
- That's Casey's recipe
for corned beef.

03:35.606 --> 03:37.521
He's passing you the torch.

03:40.524 --> 03:44.354
[sentimental music]

03:44.398 --> 03:45.616
[alarm blares]

03:45.660 --> 03:48.924
- Engine 51, Truck 81,
Ambulance 61.

03:48.967 --> 03:52.014
Person trapped. 3623...

03:52.057 --> 03:55.017
[suspenseful music]

03:55.060 --> 03:59.587
♪

03:59.630 --> 04:01.937
- You must be Gallo.
Good to meet you.

04:01.980 --> 04:04.461
Lieutenant Pelham.
- Yeah, same.

04:04.505 --> 04:07.508
[sirens wailing]

04:19.781 --> 04:21.739
- All right, grab your machine
tools and some cribbing.

04:21.783 --> 04:22.784
Let's get in there.

04:22.827 --> 04:25.961
[dramatic music]

04:26.004 --> 04:28.746
All right, give us some room.
- Make room, make room.

04:28.790 --> 04:31.053
- Give us some room, folks.
- Thank you.

04:31.096 --> 04:33.795
- He was not supposed to be
on the conveyor.

04:33.838 --> 04:36.537
- [panting]

04:36.580 --> 04:37.886
Please help me!

04:37.929 --> 04:40.584
- All right, take him
to the service box, now.

04:40.628 --> 04:43.326
- Mouch, lock out, tag out,
grab all the webbing we got.

04:43.370 --> 04:44.371
- Copy that.

04:44.414 --> 04:45.546
- Gallo, I want you

04:45.589 --> 04:47.112
to stabilize the arm
and turntable.

04:47.156 --> 04:49.071
Let's have the 9 inch
cut-off standing by.

04:49.114 --> 04:50.115
- On it.

04:50.159 --> 04:57.297
♪

05:04.739 --> 05:06.784
- [speaking incoherently]

05:06.828 --> 05:07.916
- Try not to talk.

05:07.959 --> 05:09.483
Try not to talk.
You're doing great.

05:12.573 --> 05:14.139
- What you need, Lieutenant?

05:14.183 --> 05:15.880
- Let's lash those
wrapping arms down.

05:15.924 --> 05:17.012
- Copy that.

05:17.055 --> 05:18.013
- I've got a clear view
of the bolt.

05:18.056 --> 05:19.014
Gonna cut, Lieutenant.

05:19.057 --> 05:20.581
- Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa! Stop!

05:21.843 --> 05:23.366
If that arm has
any tension built up,

05:23.410 --> 05:25.063
it'll move as soon as you
clear the obstruction.

05:25.107 --> 05:26.804
- I know, and I stabilized
it with wedges.

05:26.848 --> 05:29.067
- And if the wedges fail,
then what?

05:29.111 --> 05:31.374
Get up there and lash down
those arms with webbing.

05:31.418 --> 05:32.984
Now.

05:33.028 --> 05:34.638
- On it, Lieutenant.

05:36.510 --> 05:37.946
- More trauma pads.

05:37.989 --> 05:39.991
- Here you go. Here.

05:40.035 --> 05:46.911
♪

05:49.087 --> 05:51.655
- Good to go here, Lieutenant.
- All right.

05:51.699 --> 05:53.744
Now start cutting.

05:53.788 --> 05:56.834
- Cutting.
[saw buzzing]

05:56.878 --> 05:59.402
[worker yelling]

06:01.143 --> 06:03.928
Clear.
[metal groans]

06:03.972 --> 06:08.585
- Okay, on my three.
One, two, three.

06:11.675 --> 06:14.678
- [groaning]

06:14.722 --> 06:15.853
- Leg is free.

06:15.897 --> 06:18.116
- All right, great work,
everyone.

06:18.160 --> 06:20.858
Let's pack up.

06:20.902 --> 06:22.207
- Those wedges totally
would've held.

06:22.251 --> 06:29.389
♪

06:35.438 --> 06:35.830
.

06:35.873 --> 06:37.919
- I'm honestly relieved to know

06:37.962 --> 06:40.878
that Mosiah had nothing
to do with the fire.

06:40.922 --> 06:43.315
But if it wasn't him,
I have no idea

06:43.359 --> 06:47.145
why Father Anthony
pointed you in my direction.

06:47.189 --> 06:50.932
- We understand the archdiocese
was investigating him.

06:50.975 --> 06:52.629
- Can you tell us anything
about that?

06:52.673 --> 06:54.283
- Nothing to tell.

06:54.326 --> 06:57.199
There's absolutely nothing
to it.

07:02.639 --> 07:07.165
They opened an investigation
based on an anonymous tip,

07:07.209 --> 07:09.385
and they found
nothing improper.

07:09.429 --> 07:11.474
- Do you have any idea
who made the accusation?

07:11.518 --> 07:13.171
- You have to understand,

07:13.215 --> 07:17.262
the church is as divided as any
other institution these days.

07:17.306 --> 07:20.962
You've got some folks
who've gotten very rigid

07:21.005 --> 07:23.181
about what it means
to be a "proper" Catholic.

07:23.225 --> 07:26.054
- Father Anthony's not
in that camp?

07:26.097 --> 07:29.666
- He made it his mission
to minister to the needy,

07:29.710 --> 07:32.190
the sick, the outcast.

07:32.234 --> 07:35.498
And believe it or not,
that ruffles some feathers.

07:35.542 --> 07:38.545
I'm sure that's at the bottom
of the accusations against him.

07:38.588 --> 07:43.245
But a brutal attack
over matters of doctrine?

07:43.288 --> 07:45.029
[suspenseful music]

07:45.073 --> 07:46.509
I can't imagine.

07:46.553 --> 07:48.903
- You'd be surprised what
some people are capable of.

07:52.428 --> 07:55.213
- Thank you for your time,
Sister.

07:55.257 --> 07:59.261
Please keep thinking on it.
If anything comes to mind--

07:59.304 --> 08:01.437
- I'll reach out.
- Thank you.

08:05.093 --> 08:06.529
- Where to next?

08:06.573 --> 08:08.531
- Arsonists, they don't just
wake up one day and decide

08:08.575 --> 08:10.054
to burn down
a church during mass.

08:10.098 --> 08:12.535
They start small,
work up their courage.

08:12.579 --> 08:14.058
- Then let's turn back
the clock,

08:14.102 --> 08:15.320
see if there were
any past incidents

08:15.364 --> 08:17.105
that slipped
through the cracks.

08:29.596 --> 08:32.207
- Hey.

08:32.250 --> 08:34.165
Maybe those wedges
would've held.

08:34.209 --> 08:37.125
Maybe they only held
because of the webbing.

08:37.168 --> 08:38.343
We don't know.

08:38.387 --> 08:40.084
And when we don't know,
we play it safe.

08:40.128 --> 08:41.303
- Oh, I hear you.

08:41.346 --> 08:42.652
I-I was just trying
to save time.

08:42.696 --> 08:45.133
See, I'm used to having
a little more latitude

08:45.176 --> 08:46.438
to act on my own.

08:46.482 --> 08:47.657
Casey, our old captain,
he knew that

08:47.701 --> 08:50.442
I had a pretty
good nose for risk-taking.

08:50.486 --> 08:53.184
- Oh yeah?

08:53.228 --> 08:55.099
I'm not Casey.

08:55.143 --> 08:58.233
And when I give you an order,
I expect you to follow it.

08:58.276 --> 09:01.453
We clear?

09:01.497 --> 09:02.498
Good.

09:06.763 --> 09:10.506
- Hey, don't worry about that.

09:10.550 --> 09:12.639
He's just trying to mark his--
- I get it.

09:12.682 --> 09:17.600
♪

09:17.644 --> 09:20.603
- Mouch, you have a sec
for Chief Boden?

09:20.647 --> 09:22.736
- Sure.

09:22.779 --> 09:24.781
- Yes.
I've seen both proposals.

09:24.825 --> 09:26.000
Neither has the numbers

09:26.043 --> 09:28.176
that the CFD are willing
to sign off on.

09:30.178 --> 09:32.615
Yeah, well, you just have
to let me know.

09:32.659 --> 09:33.747
Thank you.

09:36.445 --> 09:39.404
- Proposals and numbers.
- Nonstop thrills.

09:39.448 --> 09:44.061
Anyway, I wanted to see
how things are going on truck.

09:44.105 --> 09:46.150
How's Pelham?

09:46.194 --> 09:48.065
- Seems like a good guy.
- Yeah.

09:48.109 --> 09:50.590
He was a floater over on 77,
they loved him.

09:52.679 --> 09:55.420
But he's got to be
the right fit.

09:55.464 --> 09:58.162
- Are you thinking about
keeping him around for more

09:58.206 --> 10:01.122
than a couple of shifts?
- Too soon to say.

10:01.165 --> 10:03.211
I don't want a revolving
door of lieutenants,

10:03.254 --> 10:05.692
so I'm keeping an eye out.

10:08.216 --> 10:11.567
- Hope it's not
out of line to ask, but...

10:11.611 --> 10:14.744
doesn't Kidd seem like the
natural replacement for Casey?

10:14.788 --> 10:16.659
- And she's not back yet.

10:18.574 --> 10:20.576
I don't have an answer
for that right now.

10:23.100 --> 10:24.667
- Fair enough.

10:24.711 --> 10:27.278
[phone ringing]

10:27.322 --> 10:29.585
I'll let you get to it.

10:29.629 --> 10:30.717
- Yep.

10:32.893 --> 10:37.158
Hey, Mouch, um, keep me posted.

10:37.201 --> 10:39.421
- Will do, Chief.
Hang in there.

10:41.597 --> 10:43.468
- Yeah.

10:43.512 --> 10:46.515
- Look at that smirk.
Ah, he's such a wiseacre.

10:46.558 --> 10:47.864
- He looks just like you.
- Yeah.

10:47.908 --> 10:49.649
They always do
when they're born.

10:49.692 --> 10:54.218
Then suddenly, you got five
little Cindys eyeballing you.

10:54.262 --> 10:57.569
- Oh, look.
Deep in thought there.

10:57.613 --> 10:59.659
What are you
thinkin' about, Otis?

10:59.702 --> 11:01.225
Ah, he's gonna be
such a brainiac.

11:01.269 --> 11:03.488
You can just tell.

11:03.532 --> 11:05.273
- Takes after Chloe.

11:05.316 --> 11:07.231
- We gotta get moving on a plan
for Winterfest.

11:07.275 --> 11:09.364
It's our best shot
to get seen and sipped

11:09.407 --> 11:11.453
by all the top bar
and liquor store owners.

11:11.496 --> 11:13.760
- Yeah, we need the perfect
beer for the occasion.

11:13.803 --> 11:16.632
And we need to reserve a tent.

11:16.676 --> 11:19.591
- Which means we should reach
out to Cara and get her help.

11:19.635 --> 11:21.202
- Didn't think you were
the biggest fan of hers.

11:21.245 --> 11:22.682
- We're already in bed
with her,

11:22.725 --> 11:24.509
we may as well use her
and Bare Moon's connections

11:24.553 --> 11:26.381
for all they're worth.

11:26.424 --> 11:28.600
Huh.

11:28.644 --> 11:29.732
What's that look about?

11:29.776 --> 11:31.342
Did you get
bathroom duty again?

11:31.386 --> 11:34.258
- No, I'm just a little
hung over, that's all.

11:36.304 --> 11:38.915
- Speaking of--how would you
feel about calling Cara,

11:38.959 --> 11:42.179
asking her to meet us
at Molly's, talk Winterfest?

11:42.223 --> 11:43.354
- Sure. She'd be glad to.

11:43.398 --> 11:45.356
She was just
texting me about it.

11:45.400 --> 11:48.403
- Oh, so, you--you guys have
your own text chain going?

11:52.581 --> 11:55.279
- You know, I'm gonna--
I'm gonna call her now.

11:56.759 --> 11:58.500
- Wow.

11:58.543 --> 12:00.415
You don't have to ask him
twice to reach out to Cara.

12:00.458 --> 12:02.243
He is all over that.

12:04.332 --> 12:05.376
Just saying.

12:05.420 --> 12:08.466
Winterfest, here we come.

12:08.510 --> 12:10.642
- Hmm.
- Yay.

12:10.686 --> 12:12.296
- Here's one.

12:12.340 --> 12:15.386
A grease fire in the kitchen
of First Baptist back in 2009.

12:15.430 --> 12:17.780
I know it's not
a Catholic church.

12:17.824 --> 12:19.651
- And it was 12 years ago.

12:19.695 --> 12:21.871
If this guy started to set fire
to churches way back then,

12:21.915 --> 12:23.481
we would've
heard more from him.

12:23.525 --> 12:24.787
There's got to be
something more recent.

12:24.831 --> 12:26.267
- But we've looked
at everything.

12:26.310 --> 12:28.399
Church fires,
fires involving animals.

12:28.443 --> 12:30.140
There are no obvious hits.

12:34.014 --> 12:35.798
You got something?

12:35.842 --> 12:38.453
- 746 West 19th.

12:38.496 --> 12:40.411
- Dumpster fire behind
an apartment building?

12:40.455 --> 12:42.979
- It was two months ago.
- Yeah.

12:43.023 --> 12:44.502
I'm not seeing the connection.

12:44.546 --> 12:46.548
- That's because it was
reported by a tenant

12:46.591 --> 12:47.679
of the apartment building,

12:47.723 --> 12:49.551
but the dumpster was
in an alley

12:49.594 --> 12:53.685
between the building
and a Catholic church.

12:53.729 --> 12:55.339
[suspenseful music]

12:55.383 --> 12:56.645
- Okay.

12:56.688 --> 12:58.821
If you think
it's worth checking out.

12:58.865 --> 13:02.520
- Until we find a better lead.
Van Meter.

13:02.564 --> 13:04.348
- Hey, what's wrong, boss?

13:04.392 --> 13:06.437
- Father Anthony suffered
some kind of complication.

13:08.309 --> 13:09.353
He didn't make it.

13:09.397 --> 13:14.968
♪

13:21.235 --> 13:21.452
.

13:21.496 --> 13:24.107
- These hydraulic lines
look solid.

13:24.151 --> 13:25.282
Nice work there.

13:27.807 --> 13:30.113
Everything all right,
Lieutenant?

13:30.157 --> 13:33.682
- Yeah, yeah.
Uh, you seen Gallo?

13:33.725 --> 13:35.249
- Did you try the bunk room?

13:35.292 --> 13:38.078
- Nah.

13:38.121 --> 13:40.254
- Anything I can help with?
- Nah.

13:40.297 --> 13:43.213
We just got off
on the wrong foot.

13:43.257 --> 13:45.825
You know, I don't like having
to come down on any of my guys

13:45.868 --> 13:47.348
right at the jump like that.

13:47.391 --> 13:49.089
- Don't worry.
Gallo can handle it.

13:49.132 --> 13:50.307
- Eh.

13:50.351 --> 13:52.048
Tension's not good
for the team.

13:55.965 --> 13:57.880
Hey, let me ask you something.

13:57.924 --> 13:59.142
Is it true that Casey
would just

13:59.186 --> 14:00.970
let him off the leash on calls?

14:01.014 --> 14:05.409
- Well, Casey really took
Gallo under his wing.

14:05.453 --> 14:09.065
And sure, Casey had to rein him
in here and there,

14:09.109 --> 14:13.156
but less as time went by.

14:13.200 --> 14:16.159
- Captain Casey meant a lot
to this house, huh?

14:16.203 --> 14:18.509
- [sighs]

14:18.553 --> 14:22.296
More than I could put
into words, to be honest.

14:22.339 --> 14:24.472
We were real lucky to have him.
- Hmm.

14:24.515 --> 14:26.996
[sentimental music]

14:27.040 --> 14:30.913
Well, he was lucky too.

14:30.957 --> 14:35.004
You know, being in a house
like this,

14:35.048 --> 14:36.963
that kind of loyalty
from his crew.

14:39.269 --> 14:41.228
Anyway, thanks for the help,
Mouch.

14:45.928 --> 14:47.974
- We really didn't think
much of it, to be honest.

14:48.017 --> 14:49.410
We put the fire out
with a mop bucket

14:49.453 --> 14:51.020
before your people
even got here.

14:51.064 --> 14:53.109
- Do you have any idea
how it might have started?

14:53.153 --> 14:55.938
- The firefighters said it was
probably just a cigarette butt.

14:55.982 --> 14:57.766
We try to keep it
locked up now.

14:59.855 --> 15:02.771
- Around the time of the fire,
was there anyone acting strange

15:02.814 --> 15:05.556
or--or threatening
towards you or your staff?

15:05.600 --> 15:08.342
- There were a few unpleasant
messages in the comment box,

15:08.385 --> 15:11.084
but no, no threats.

15:11.127 --> 15:12.302
- What kind of messages?

15:12.346 --> 15:14.130
- Oh, I'm just referring to
some tension

15:14.174 --> 15:16.785
at our parish
the last few years.

15:16.828 --> 15:19.396
Some people,
older members mostly,

15:19.440 --> 15:22.312
complaining that we've gotten
a little too "woke,"

15:22.356 --> 15:24.924
I guess you'd say.

15:24.967 --> 15:27.883
But those folks
are all well-meaning.

15:31.191 --> 15:33.410
- Um, what is it, Father?

15:33.454 --> 15:35.369
- There was one thing.

15:35.412 --> 15:36.979
I guess it was around
the time of the fire,

15:37.023 --> 15:38.938
now that I'm thinking about it.

15:38.981 --> 15:43.290
The altar boys discovered some
missals that had been defaced.

15:43.333 --> 15:45.074
Drawings, mostly.

15:45.118 --> 15:47.294
I thought it was some bored kid
entertaining himself,

15:47.337 --> 15:50.601
but it seemed more
than doodling.

15:50.645 --> 15:52.603
It seemed angry.

15:52.647 --> 15:54.083
- Can we see one
of these missals?

15:54.127 --> 15:56.085
- We tried to weed
them all out,

15:56.129 --> 15:57.869
but there might be some
in the recycling still.

15:57.913 --> 15:59.088
Let me check for you.

15:59.132 --> 16:02.570
[suspenseful music]

16:02.613 --> 16:06.095
- Maybe our arsonist was some
kind of religious hardliner,

16:06.139 --> 16:08.271
targeting progressive churches?

16:08.315 --> 16:09.751
- So what you're saying is,

16:09.794 --> 16:13.146
my dumpster fire lead wasn't
a complete waste of time.

16:15.235 --> 16:17.193
- Found a bunch of old missals
back there.

16:17.237 --> 16:18.934
Not sure any of them
are defaced,

16:18.978 --> 16:20.588
but you're welcome
to have a look.

16:22.155 --> 16:23.460
Take them with you.

16:26.594 --> 16:28.204
- Thank you, Father.

16:28.248 --> 16:31.991
♪

16:35.951 --> 16:37.909
- Getting ready for your trip?

16:37.953 --> 16:39.999
- Yeah, Casey hasn't had
a chance to see the sights,

16:40.042 --> 16:42.479
so we're gonna do
all the cheesy touristy stuff.

16:42.523 --> 16:44.003
I can't wait.

16:44.046 --> 16:46.353
- How's he--
how's he doing there?

16:46.396 --> 16:47.571
- He's good.

16:47.615 --> 16:50.531
Really busy
between work and the boys.

16:50.574 --> 16:52.924
Ben got into some advanced
coding class,

16:52.968 --> 16:56.319
and Griffin is talking about
the fire academy after college.

16:56.363 --> 16:58.191
- Wow.
[chuckles]

16:58.234 --> 17:00.454
I guess Casey's feeling, um,

17:00.497 --> 17:04.066
pretty settled, then,
in Oregon.

17:04.110 --> 17:07.026
- He misses everyone here,
of course.

17:07.069 --> 17:09.028
But with the boys
doing so well,

17:09.071 --> 17:11.508
he knows he did
the right thing.

17:11.552 --> 17:13.336
- That's--that's great.

17:13.380 --> 17:15.077
You'll have to give him
my best.

17:15.121 --> 17:16.165
When are you--

17:16.209 --> 17:18.907
- Oh, ten days and one hour.

17:18.950 --> 17:21.040
Oh and no,
strike that--59 minutes.

17:21.083 --> 17:22.606
[alarm blares]

17:22.650 --> 17:28.003
- Engine 51, Truck 81,
Ambulance 61, automatic alarm.

17:28.047 --> 17:29.222
- Hey, Chief. What's up?

17:31.746 --> 17:34.923
[sirens wailing]

17:38.187 --> 17:40.581
- Not exactly an inferno.

17:40.624 --> 17:42.365
- Looks like a false alarm.

17:52.593 --> 17:54.551
- You coming, Seager?
- Uh, yeah.

17:54.595 --> 17:56.249
I-I think I'll keep
chipping away at these.

18:00.079 --> 18:01.732
- I'm awfully sorry
for the trouble.

18:01.776 --> 18:05.475
I have no idea
who pulled the alarm.

18:05.519 --> 18:07.042
- It's okay, Father.

18:07.086 --> 18:09.088
The most important thing
is keeping everybody safe.

18:09.131 --> 18:10.741
We'll let you know
when you can go back inside.

18:10.785 --> 18:12.526
- Just another false alarm?

18:12.569 --> 18:14.093
- All clear, Chief.

18:14.136 --> 18:16.486
Not so much
as a puff of smoke in there.

18:16.530 --> 18:18.097
- Ah, there you go.

18:18.140 --> 18:20.229
Sorry for dragging you
out for nothing.

18:20.273 --> 18:22.971
I heard "church"
and my radar went up.

18:23.014 --> 18:24.103
- Yeah, me too.

18:26.105 --> 18:27.541
All right, thanks, Chief.

18:27.584 --> 18:28.585
- Thank you, Father.

18:30.674 --> 18:33.634
- All units, back in service.

18:35.636 --> 18:40.249
- Oh, Mrs. Callahan, hi.
- Hello--ah! Sylvie.

18:40.293 --> 18:41.511
- You look great.

18:41.555 --> 18:43.774
You must be taking
your Trexall, I can tell.

18:43.818 --> 18:45.602
Did you walk all the way here
from your house?

18:45.646 --> 18:50.129
- Don't look so impressed,
it's only three blocks.

18:50.172 --> 18:53.262
I don't care how permissive
Saint Dom's gets,

18:53.306 --> 18:56.396
I'll keep coming here
till they put me in the ground.

18:56.439 --> 18:59.225
- Oh, well, that'll be a while,
so take care of yourself.

19:04.491 --> 19:05.622
- Just another dead end.

19:05.666 --> 19:08.321
- Yeah, well,
I don't think this is.

19:10.192 --> 19:13.195
[suspenseful music]

19:13.239 --> 19:16.720
- "Damnable heresies bring
swift destruction."

19:16.764 --> 19:18.461
- This has to be our arsonist.

19:18.505 --> 19:24.163
♪

19:27.601 --> 19:27.775
.

19:27.818 --> 19:29.907
- Van Meter's not gonna
bother you.

19:29.951 --> 19:32.606
Okay, have a good day.
Hey, Brett.

19:33.955 --> 19:35.739
- Hey!
- Hey.

19:35.783 --> 19:37.785
- Do you get to go home now?

19:37.828 --> 19:39.787
- No, I'm on my way
to headquarters.

19:39.830 --> 19:41.832
- Oh. I'm sorry to hear that.
- [chuckles]

19:41.876 --> 19:43.530
You talked to Kidd lately?

19:43.573 --> 19:44.792
I can see that she's extended

19:44.835 --> 19:46.228
her furlough
by another two weeks.

19:46.272 --> 19:48.448
- Yeah, she's pretty invested
in getting

19:48.491 --> 19:50.537
those Girls on Fire programs
up and running.

19:50.580 --> 19:52.452
It's been kind of strange
with her

19:52.495 --> 19:55.106
on the East Coast
and Casey in Oregon.

19:55.150 --> 19:57.718
Everything feels
a little askew.

19:57.761 --> 19:59.154
- Yeah, I agree.

19:59.198 --> 20:01.504
- But change can be good,
right?

20:01.548 --> 20:06.553
You know, brings excitement
and new energy, new challenges.

20:06.596 --> 20:07.989
What does Donna think
of your new job?

20:08.032 --> 20:09.556
- She's always happy

20:09.599 --> 20:11.297
when I'm not running
into a burning building.

20:11.340 --> 20:14.038
Doesn't bother her one bit that
she's married to a desk jockey.

20:14.082 --> 20:15.257
- [laughs]

20:15.301 --> 20:17.128
Well, good luck
over there today, boss.

20:17.172 --> 20:19.087
- I'm gonna need it.

20:24.745 --> 20:26.268
- Hey, one black and tan.

20:26.312 --> 20:29.532
You know,
that's Gallo's drink too.

20:29.576 --> 20:30.838
- So I hear.
- Yeah.

20:32.318 --> 20:35.146
- So you telling me
that Pelham's the guy

20:35.190 --> 20:37.975
with the double rescue
at the back of the Yards?

20:38.019 --> 20:39.977
The one that got splashed
all over the news.

20:40.021 --> 20:42.284
- Yeah, he was floating at 41
when it happened.

20:42.328 --> 20:43.807
- Oh.

20:43.851 --> 20:46.593
You know, guys like that,
sometimes they get a big head,

20:46.636 --> 20:50.597
but you know, Pelham,
he seems pretty low key.

20:52.120 --> 20:55.123
I'm telling you now,
he's going places.

21:04.350 --> 21:06.569
- Thanks.

21:06.613 --> 21:09.268
- I've been asking around
about Casey.

21:09.311 --> 21:10.878
Sounds like he was
one hell of an officer.

21:12.793 --> 21:13.794
- He was.

21:16.710 --> 21:17.711
- You know...

21:20.191 --> 21:23.151
Adjusting to new
leadership is always hard.

21:23.194 --> 21:24.326
Trust me.

21:24.370 --> 21:26.110
Had to do
a lot of it in my career.

21:27.982 --> 21:31.681
But a great firefighter has
to be adaptable above all else.

21:31.725 --> 21:33.553
Just like no two fires
are the same.

21:33.596 --> 21:36.077
- Hey, you.
- Hey.

21:36.120 --> 21:37.208
- Oh, sorry.

21:37.252 --> 21:39.123
I hope I'm not
interrupting anything.

21:39.167 --> 21:41.343
- Not at all.
- Sorry.

21:41.387 --> 21:44.041
Cara, this
is Lieutenant Pelham.

21:44.085 --> 21:46.696
- [chuckles]
Jason.

21:49.046 --> 21:50.700
- Sorry to rush out,
but we actually have plans.

21:50.744 --> 21:52.659
We gotta get moving, right?

21:52.702 --> 21:55.270
- Yes. Definitely.

21:55.314 --> 21:58.099
It was nice to meet you, Jason.

21:58.142 --> 22:00.101
- Oh, thanks for the beer,
Lieutenant.

22:04.410 --> 22:07.804
- Guess we're not talking
about Winterfest tonight.

22:07.848 --> 22:08.936
- Guess not.

22:10.807 --> 22:12.722
What's going on there?

22:12.766 --> 22:14.071
- Uh, nothing.

22:14.115 --> 22:15.638
It's just a side stitch
that keeps bugging me.

22:15.682 --> 22:18.206
When I said we were in bed
with Cara and Bare Moon,

22:18.249 --> 22:21.252
I didn't mean he should
literally get in bed with her.

22:21.296 --> 22:22.819
- Okay.

22:22.863 --> 22:26.736
Look, they could just be
going to grab a bite somewhere.

22:26.780 --> 22:32.089
And he gets to avoid
his new boss at the same time.

22:32.133 --> 22:34.265
- Yeah, Gallo is not a fan.

22:34.309 --> 22:36.703
Good thing Pelham's only
with us for a shift or two.

22:36.746 --> 22:38.618
- [scoffs]

22:38.661 --> 22:41.838
- "There were false prophets
among the people,

22:41.882 --> 22:44.624
"even as there will be
false teachers among you

22:44.667 --> 22:47.235
"who will secretly
bring in damnable heresies,

22:47.278 --> 22:50.151
and bring upon themselves
swift destruction."

22:51.979 --> 22:53.894
- Sounds pretty Old Testament.

22:56.984 --> 22:58.899
- No.

22:58.942 --> 23:03.033
2 Peter 2.

23:03.077 --> 23:05.993
- Don't laugh at me.
- I'm not laughing.

23:07.777 --> 23:11.041
Anyway, it seems like
we're dealing with somebody

23:11.085 --> 23:13.348
who thinks
these so-called false teachers

23:13.392 --> 23:15.089
are destroying Catholicism.

23:15.132 --> 23:19.441
Progressive priests like
Father Anthony, Father Marcus.

23:19.485 --> 23:24.968
Which means our arsonist
isn't some psychopath.

23:25.012 --> 23:28.189
This is very personal to him.

23:31.192 --> 23:33.673
- I think I found something.

23:33.716 --> 23:36.893
[suspenseful music]

23:36.937 --> 23:39.766
The arrow going
through the heart.

23:39.809 --> 23:43.465
In every book,
it points to this same verse.

23:43.509 --> 23:45.772
"The Lord is my light
and my salvation;

23:45.815 --> 23:47.034
whom shall I fear?"

23:48.949 --> 23:51.342
- Wait a second.
I-I know that quote.

23:51.386 --> 23:52.474
- Well, you've been staring

23:52.518 --> 23:54.171
at Bible study websites
for hours now.

23:54.215 --> 23:56.217
- No.
No, that's not why.

24:01.788 --> 24:02.832
I got it.

24:02.876 --> 24:09.317
♪

24:09.360 --> 24:11.058
Good morning, Sister.

24:11.101 --> 24:12.146
- Hello.

24:12.189 --> 24:14.191
You've heard
about Father Anthony?

24:14.235 --> 24:15.497
- Yes.

24:15.541 --> 24:18.935
And we're very sorry
for your loss.

24:18.979 --> 24:22.765
- It's a profound loss
for this entire community.

24:22.809 --> 24:23.810
- No doubt.

24:26.247 --> 24:28.031
Sister, can we come in?

24:28.075 --> 24:29.424
We need to talk to you.

24:31.948 --> 24:33.472
- Of course.

24:35.299 --> 24:38.041
How can I help?
- Can I ask where you got this?

24:41.044 --> 24:42.481
- It was a gift
from Mr. Muller.

24:42.524 --> 24:44.831
Our former groundskeeper. Why?

24:44.874 --> 24:46.397
- What can you tell us
about him?

24:46.441 --> 24:48.443
- I don't know.
He was a good employee.

24:48.487 --> 24:52.142
Always on time.
Kept to himself.

24:52.186 --> 24:53.230
Very devout.

24:53.274 --> 24:54.754
- Where is he now?

24:54.797 --> 24:56.233
- He left
a couple of weeks ago.

24:56.277 --> 24:58.018
Said he found a better job.

24:58.061 --> 24:59.019
- He left on good terms?

24:59.062 --> 25:02.065
- Yes. I was happy for him.

25:02.109 --> 25:05.242
That's actually why I wasn't in
church on the day of the fire.

25:05.286 --> 25:07.941
I was interviewing
a possible replacement.

25:10.944 --> 25:14.251
- And Father Anthony knew this?
- Of course.

25:14.295 --> 25:17.124
He was aware
of all personnel matters.

25:19.387 --> 25:20.475
What's wrong?

25:20.519 --> 25:21.607
- That's the question

25:21.650 --> 25:23.391
Father Anthony wanted us
to ask you.

25:23.434 --> 25:25.132
Where were you during the fire?

25:25.175 --> 25:27.482
- He wanted you to tell us
about Mr. Muller.

25:33.357 --> 25:34.924
- The search
for a new groundskeeper

25:34.968 --> 25:36.926
was put on hold after the fire,

25:36.970 --> 25:39.538
so no one's been in here
since Mr. Muller.

25:39.581 --> 25:46.545
♪

25:56.642 --> 25:58.078
- Do you notice anything
unusual

25:58.121 --> 25:59.601
or out of place, Sister?

25:59.645 --> 26:01.429
- Looks like
he cleaned it out.

26:03.344 --> 26:06.477
- What was over here?
- Some bags.

26:06.521 --> 26:09.219
I'm not sure--soil or mulch.

26:09.263 --> 26:11.482
Something from
the garden supply store.

26:11.526 --> 26:12.919
- How many bags were there?

26:12.962 --> 26:15.356
- I don't know. A dozen or so?

26:22.885 --> 26:24.147
- Whatever this guy
is planning,

26:24.191 --> 26:26.323
it involves a whole lot
of ammonium nitrate.

26:31.807 --> 26:31.981
.

26:32.025 --> 26:34.854
- I'm looking at a purchase
order from the school.

26:34.897 --> 26:36.377
This Larry Muller could have
as much as five hundred pounds

26:36.420 --> 26:38.335
of ammonium nitrate-based
fertilizer in his possession.

26:38.379 --> 26:39.902
And we believe him
to be capable of planning

26:39.946 --> 26:41.643
a mass casualty incident.

26:41.687 --> 26:43.471
Is that urgent enough for you?

26:45.473 --> 26:46.909
What's driving this guy,
do we know?

26:46.953 --> 26:48.781
- Seems like he has an issue
with Catholic priests

26:48.824 --> 26:49.956
who he thinks are too lax.

26:49.999 --> 26:51.305
- His methods are escalating

26:51.348 --> 26:52.654
with every church
he goes after.

26:52.698 --> 26:54.308
And the fact that he quit
his job makes me worry

26:54.351 --> 26:55.744
that he's getting ready
for something big.

26:55.788 --> 26:57.572
- So what's his next target?
- He might go back

26:57.616 --> 26:59.443
to Blessed Mother or continue
on to some other church.

26:59.487 --> 27:01.924
Impossible to say.

27:01.968 --> 27:03.665
- Good. We'll head right over.
Thanks.

27:03.709 --> 27:04.710
- Atwater's getting the
warrant now.

27:04.753 --> 27:05.711
He'll meet us at the house.

27:05.754 --> 27:06.973
- Great, let's go.

27:10.629 --> 27:11.891
- How's it going there, Pelham?

27:11.934 --> 27:13.936
- No complaints. Oh, hey.

27:13.980 --> 27:16.112
Pete Tipler from 111 says hi.

27:16.156 --> 27:17.505
- How do you know Tipler?

27:17.548 --> 27:19.550
- Ah, worked together
for a couple months.

27:19.594 --> 27:20.813
I filled in for McPherson

27:20.856 --> 27:22.684
when he was laid up
after back surgery.

27:22.728 --> 27:24.817
- Oh. That was last year, huh?

27:24.860 --> 27:27.080
- Yeah. He's much better now.

27:28.821 --> 27:31.606
- Good to hear.
- See you.

27:36.480 --> 27:38.874
All right, guys.
We're gonna try something.

27:40.571 --> 27:42.138
- What's this?

27:42.182 --> 27:43.705
- One of the best parts about
being a reliever is you get

27:43.749 --> 27:45.707
to see all the different ways
of doing things.

27:45.751 --> 27:48.057
Now, what you have there is,
in my experience,

27:48.101 --> 27:50.494
the most efficient compartment
organization there is.

27:52.105 --> 27:54.107
- Casey's system was based on
15 years' experience

27:54.150 --> 27:56.500
running Truck 81.

27:56.544 --> 27:57.850
Good luck improving on that.

28:00.766 --> 28:02.419
[tense music]

28:02.463 --> 28:06.815
- You know, one day I hope
I have a firefighter

28:06.859 --> 28:09.035
who gets that starry-eyed
when he talks about me.

28:12.516 --> 28:14.823
I'll tell you what, Gallo.

28:14.867 --> 28:19.436
When I leave 51, you can put it
back the way Casey had it.

28:19.480 --> 28:23.049
Until then, let's do it my way.

28:23.092 --> 28:30.099
♪

28:31.927 --> 28:33.799
- When does he leave?

28:44.548 --> 28:45.898
- Flores, Jackson,
cover the back.

28:45.941 --> 28:48.161
- Copy that.

28:48.204 --> 28:49.423
- Is this your friend
you said tried

28:49.466 --> 28:51.730
to knock you down the stairs?

28:51.773 --> 28:54.907
- Just might be, yeah.
- Okay, let's go.

28:54.950 --> 29:01.957
♪

29:13.186 --> 29:14.840
- How you doing, ma'am?

29:14.883 --> 29:16.929
We're looking for Larry Muller.
Does he live here?

29:18.844 --> 29:21.672
- Oh, he--he hasn't been home
in over a week.

29:21.716 --> 29:24.806
I don't know where he is.
I've been worried sick.

29:24.850 --> 29:26.895
My son, he isn't well.

29:26.939 --> 29:29.071
Um, I don't--I don't
have the key.

29:29.115 --> 29:36.122
♪

29:55.010 --> 29:56.577
- What the hell is this?

30:04.541 --> 30:06.674
Okay,
you all are probably right.

30:16.075 --> 30:17.816
- Severide.

30:21.732 --> 30:23.299
- Has Larry hurt anyone?

30:23.343 --> 30:25.084
- Yes, ma'am. He has.

30:25.127 --> 30:27.521
- Looks like he wants
to hurt a lot more.

30:32.700 --> 30:34.180
What's this right here? A bomb?

30:39.620 --> 30:41.535
- Looks like
a fuel injection system.

30:53.895 --> 30:55.027
Seager, come here.

30:57.812 --> 30:59.292
Is that Saint Dominic's?

30:59.335 --> 31:00.728
- Sure is.

31:05.298 --> 31:07.082
- This is nice. Lemon scent?

31:07.126 --> 31:10.303
- Orange.
- You sure?

31:10.346 --> 31:12.044
- Hey, Ritter.
Come here for a sec.

31:12.087 --> 31:14.916
Does it smell like lemon
or orange to you?

31:14.960 --> 31:17.701
- It's orange.
- Hey!

31:17.745 --> 31:19.007
- Did you ever find out

31:19.051 --> 31:22.184
where Gallo and Cara
went off to last night?

31:22.228 --> 31:24.708
- I didn't think it was
my business to--

31:24.752 --> 31:26.885
- But it is our business.

31:26.928 --> 31:28.234
As co-owners of Fire Goat,
we should know

31:28.277 --> 31:30.889
if he's sleeping
with our investor, right?

31:30.932 --> 31:33.282
Or whatever she is.

31:33.326 --> 31:36.764
- Violet, you do know that pain
in your side is Gallo, right?

31:36.807 --> 31:39.071
- What? Get out of here.

31:39.114 --> 31:40.855
- I think he might be right,
Violet.

31:40.899 --> 31:43.597
Your body's telling you
to pay attention.

31:43.640 --> 31:45.251
- To what?

31:45.294 --> 31:47.906
- Your feelings for Gallo.

31:47.949 --> 31:49.995
If you don't, you might
get stuck with that pain

31:50.038 --> 31:52.214
for the rest of your life.

31:52.258 --> 31:54.390
- I think
it's too much caffeine.

31:54.434 --> 31:56.262
Or I just need a new mattress.

31:56.305 --> 31:57.306
[phone dings]

32:01.920 --> 32:03.269
[alarm blares]

32:03.312 --> 32:06.402
- Engine 51, Truck 81,
Squad 3, Ambulance 61.

32:06.446 --> 32:09.666
Automatic alarm,
1334 North Flournoy.

32:09.710 --> 32:12.278
- That's Saint Dominic's
again.

32:12.321 --> 32:16.064
[sirens wailing]

32:16.108 --> 32:19.111
[suspenseful music]

32:19.154 --> 32:26.118
♪

32:26.161 --> 32:28.424
- Chief,
it's just another prank.

32:28.468 --> 32:30.731
I-I-I'm sorry
to drag you out here again.

32:30.774 --> 32:32.254
- We need to check it out,
Father.

32:32.298 --> 32:35.736
Let's get these stragglers
out of the building, shall we?

32:35.779 --> 32:37.781
Engine, Truck,

32:37.825 --> 32:39.740
sweep the inside.

32:39.783 --> 32:41.133
Squad, stand by.

32:42.482 --> 32:46.355
Herrmann, Pelham.
Give it a thorough look.

32:46.399 --> 32:48.183
Let me know
if anything seems off.

32:48.227 --> 32:49.880
- You got it, Chief.
- Okay.

32:49.924 --> 32:52.361
- Hey, this is his next target.

32:52.405 --> 32:54.102
- What? Are you sure?

32:54.146 --> 32:55.756
There's no sign of any fire.

32:55.799 --> 32:56.975
- He's not setting a fire.

32:57.018 --> 32:59.020
That last alarm pull,
he was just--

32:59.064 --> 33:01.109
he was just doing
his reconnaissance.

33:01.153 --> 33:03.372
Chief, he--he set a car bomb.

33:03.416 --> 33:06.201
- All units,
evacuate the building.

33:06.245 --> 33:08.464
Help me clear out
this parking lot right away.

33:08.508 --> 33:10.989
Now! Come on, let's go,
let's go, let's go.

33:11.032 --> 33:12.468
- You heard the man.
Let's move, let's go!

33:12.512 --> 33:16.081
[indistinct chatter]

33:16.124 --> 33:19.345
- Let's keep moving, everyone.
Keep moving, thank you.

33:19.388 --> 33:20.781
- We're moving everybody
across the street.

33:20.824 --> 33:22.826
Come on. Come on. Hey!

33:24.741 --> 33:26.047
- Hey! Hey!

33:26.091 --> 33:27.918
- Easy, folks. Slow down.

33:27.962 --> 33:30.965
[intense music]

33:31.009 --> 33:38.016
♪

33:43.064 --> 33:45.023
- Go. Go! Get back!

33:45.066 --> 33:47.155
[trigger beeping]

33:47.199 --> 33:48.200
Go!

33:49.810 --> 33:52.247
- Move!
- Back up!

33:52.291 --> 33:53.509
- Come with me.

33:53.553 --> 33:55.250
Move! Move!

33:55.294 --> 33:57.948
- Go! Get back!

34:03.563 --> 34:03.780
.

34:03.824 --> 34:05.869
[car alarm beeping]

34:05.913 --> 34:07.741
- Everybody okay?

34:07.784 --> 34:08.829
- Medic!

34:08.872 --> 34:10.918
[tense music]

34:10.961 --> 34:12.354
- You okay?
- Yeah.

34:12.398 --> 34:14.704
- How about you, Chief?
- You okay? I'm fine.

34:17.533 --> 34:18.534
Oh, God.

34:18.578 --> 34:25.585
♪

34:46.562 --> 34:48.477
- "Pride goeth
before destruction...

34:50.653 --> 34:52.264
A haughty spirit
before the fall."

34:55.919 --> 34:58.444
Proverbs 16:18.

35:20.814 --> 35:23.773
- Crazy false alarm, huh?
- Yeah.

35:26.733 --> 35:29.344
- You okay?
- Yeah.

35:29.388 --> 35:31.781
- Really?
- Uh.

35:33.392 --> 35:36.743
Casey has been wanting to do
this wildfire training program,

35:36.786 --> 35:39.702
and there's usually
a long wait list,

35:39.746 --> 35:42.662
but uh, a spot just
opened up last minute.

35:42.705 --> 35:44.011
- Oh, man. And it's--

35:44.054 --> 35:46.753
- Yeah, it's right
when I was supposed to visit.

35:46.796 --> 35:49.103
So it turns out

35:49.147 --> 35:52.802
I will not be seeing him
in seven days and six hours.

35:55.153 --> 35:58.417
- I'm sorry.
- I hate change.

35:58.460 --> 36:00.462
I don't know
why I said change was good.

36:00.506 --> 36:05.598
It's not.
It's stupid and painful.

36:05.641 --> 36:07.861
[sighs]
It messes everything up.

36:09.776 --> 36:11.038
- Yeah, it does.

36:17.479 --> 36:19.481
It messes everything up.

36:19.525 --> 36:22.789
[sentimental music]

36:22.832 --> 36:27.663
- I just--I really miss him.

36:32.102 --> 36:33.843
- I do too.

36:39.501 --> 36:40.502
[snorts]

36:43.505 --> 36:46.334
- What are you laughing about?
We're in crisis.

36:46.378 --> 36:47.770
- We totally are.

36:47.814 --> 36:51.121
But I was just thinking about
what Casey would say

36:51.165 --> 36:53.472
if he walked in here
and saw us like this.

36:53.515 --> 36:55.517
- [laughs]

36:55.561 --> 36:56.997
Well.

36:57.040 --> 36:59.695
Well, to me, he would say,

36:59.739 --> 37:05.005
"What're you doing?
I'm not dead, I'm in Oregon.

37:05.048 --> 37:06.746
"And you'll see me
in three weeks.

37:09.401 --> 37:14.493
"Things might be different,
but we're still us.

37:17.235 --> 37:19.062
So get up off that bench."

37:23.545 --> 37:27.114
- To me he'd say, "You still
crave the rolled up

37:27.157 --> 37:29.072
"newspaper, don't you, Gallo?

37:29.116 --> 37:31.466
"Are you actually gonna just
sit here and mope about

37:31.510 --> 37:32.728
"how I was your mentor?

37:32.772 --> 37:34.121
"Or are you gonna get up,
get back to work,

37:34.164 --> 37:37.690
and actually act like I was?"

37:37.733 --> 37:44.740
♪

37:54.576 --> 37:56.535
- I don't know how you go back
to chasing cats out of trees

37:56.578 --> 37:58.537
after a case
like that, Severide.

37:58.580 --> 38:00.452
- I'll manage.

38:00.495 --> 38:01.931
- I'm really glad
you were on this.

38:04.107 --> 38:05.935
- I'm glad we were both on it.

38:07.633 --> 38:09.722
- All right, now,
go on and play some cornhole

38:09.765 --> 38:12.681
or whatever it is you guys
do around here.

38:12.725 --> 38:15.815
Stick me with the paperwork
once again.

38:15.858 --> 38:17.730
- I'll make it up to you.

38:17.773 --> 38:19.471
Next round on me at Molly's.

38:21.603 --> 38:23.475
- I will take you up on that.

38:23.518 --> 38:30.525
♪

38:39.229 --> 38:40.274
[phone beeps]

38:40.318 --> 38:41.754
- You are flirting
with someone.

38:41.797 --> 38:43.277
I can see it in your fingers.

38:43.321 --> 38:45.845
- That's not a thing.
- Well?

38:47.803 --> 38:49.805
- The guy from Soul Cycle
asked me out.

38:49.849 --> 38:51.938
- Look at you.
Back in the game.

38:51.981 --> 38:53.069
- [chuckles]

38:59.249 --> 39:02.775
- Too much caffeine,
I told you.

39:02.818 --> 39:05.125
- Hey, would you all just
give me a minute?

39:05.168 --> 39:09.129
Just want to let you know
that Lieutenant Pelham

39:09.172 --> 39:10.957
will be staying on with us

39:11.000 --> 39:13.307
for the next month or so,
right?

39:13.351 --> 39:19.139
Okay, so everybody,
please make him feel at home.

39:19.182 --> 39:20.706
- Good to have you here,
Pelham.

39:20.749 --> 39:21.968
- Hey, thank you.

39:22.011 --> 39:23.230
- Great having you out there
with us today.

39:23.273 --> 39:24.753
- Thanks.

39:24.797 --> 39:25.972
- All right, lunch is up.

39:32.021 --> 39:35.024
- Hey, great work
out there today.

39:37.375 --> 39:39.507
- Gallo, is that
what I think it is?

39:39.551 --> 39:42.075
- Yeah.
Casey's corned beef.

39:42.118 --> 39:45.339
- In that case, I'm definitely
staying for lunch.

39:45.383 --> 39:49.169
- And the first plate
goes to the lieutenant.

39:49.212 --> 39:52.172
[heartfelt music]

39:52.215 --> 39:58.178
♪

39:58.221 --> 40:01.050
- Oh, ho ho.
Looks delicious.

40:01.094 --> 40:03.531
- Don't get used to it.

40:03.575 --> 40:05.185
Took a lot longer
than I realized.

40:13.976 --> 40:16.675
- I'm glad Pelham's
sticking around.

40:16.718 --> 40:18.241
He's one of the good guys.

40:24.683 --> 40:25.684
What's wrong?

40:27.163 --> 40:28.991
- I don't know.

40:29.035 --> 40:31.951
But Mouch, a guy that great,

40:31.994 --> 40:33.909
doesn't it make you
kind of wonder, you know,

40:33.953 --> 40:38.218
why he's been floating
for so long?

40:38.261 --> 40:41.134
So many different places?

40:41.177 --> 40:43.092
Never got a command of his own?

40:45.007 --> 40:46.182
- That's...

40:48.141 --> 40:49.925
A really good question.

40:49.969 --> 40:56.976
♪

41:01.763 --> 41:04.723
[dramatic music]

41:04.766 --> 41:11.773
♪

41:31.793 --> 41:34.796
[wolf howls]
